<span id="iii.xi.x-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="iii.xi.x-p1.1"></span>Chapter X.—</span>*The Bishops of Jerusalem.*

<span id="iii.xi.x-p2"></span><span class="c11"><span
id="iii.xi.x-p2.1"></span>Narcissus</span> having departed, and no one
knowing where he was, those presiding over the neighboring churches
thought it best to ordain another bishop. His name was Dius. <span
id="fr_1818"></span>[1819](#fn_1818.md) He presided but a short time, and
Germanio succeeded him. He was followed by Gordius, <span
id="fr_1819"></span>[1820](#fn_1819.md) in whose time Narcissus appeared
again, as if raised from the dead. <span
id="fr_1820"></span>[1821](#fn_1820.md) And immediately the brethren
besought him to take the episcopate, as all admired him the more on
account of his retirement and philosophy, and especially because of the
punishment with which God had avenged him.

